<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-298-574  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 298 574.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  May 1989 v6 n5 p101(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Compound documents take the state.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Millikin, Michael D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Compound documents are rapidly coming into common usage as adocument format on computers, as is evidenced by Digital'sCompound Document Architecture (CDA), the International StandardsOrganization's Office Document Architecture (ODA), Wang's WangInformation Transfer Architecture, and IBM's Mixed Object DocumentContent Architecture (MODCA).andP;  Compound documents consist of avariety of data elements in a single document, including text,data, graphics and scanned images.andP;  Such a document architectureprovide a comprehensive strategy for information storage,transparent access, analysis, integration, and disseminationacross a network.andP;  ODA is being developed as a standardarchitecture for compound documents, while IBM is trying topersuade other vendors and developers that MODCA should bestandard.andP;  ODA and CDA are the available choices for the UNIXenvironment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Composite Data StructuresTrendsSystem DesignSpecificationsText FormattingDocument Management Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>